Method Dispatch
S7 methods are registered for generic functions:
# Print method for WebSpec
method(print, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  cli_inform(c(
    "A {.cls WebSpec} with {nrow(x@data)} row{?s}",
    "*" = "Columns: {length(x@columns)}",
    "*" = "Groups: {length(x@groups)}"
  ))
  invisible(x)
}

# Plot method (renders as widget)
method(plot, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  forest_plot(x, ...)
}

# as.data.frame method
method(as.data.frame, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  x@data
}

Axis Labels
For forest plot columns, use axis_label within viz_forest() to label the x-axis:


Code
glp1_trials |&gt;
  filter(row_type == "data", group == "Main Trials") |&gt;
  head(3) |&gt;
  tabviz(
    label = "study",
    title = "Treatment Effect",
    columns = list(
      viz_forest(point = "hr", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
                 scale = "log", null_value = 1,
                 axis_label = "Hazard Ratio (95% CI)")
    )
  )

Reusable Pipelines
Encapsulate your organization’s styling standards as a function:


Code
apply_clinical_style &lt;- function(plot) {
  plot |&gt;
    set_marker_style(color = "sig_color") |&gt;
    set_row_style(bold = "is_sig") |&gt;
    set_theme("jama")
}

forest_plot(trial_a, ...) |&gt; apply_clinical_style()
forest_plot(trial_b, ...) |&gt; apply_clinical_style()

Selecting a Subgroup in Shiny
Inside Shiny, switch the active subgroup programmatically with split_tabviz_select():
observeEvent(input$region, {
  split_tabviz_select(split_tabviz_proxy("split_plot"), input$region)
})
See Shiny Integration for the full pattern.

Reactive Data Patterns
Connect the plot to reactive sources — the widget re-renders whenever the reactive changes:
server &lt;- function(input, output, session) {
  filtered_data &lt;- reactive({
    meta_data |&gt;
      dplyr::filter(region == input$region)
  })

  output$plot &lt;- renderTabviz({
    tabviz(filtered_data(),
      label = "study",
      columns = list(
        viz_forest(point = "hr", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
                   scale = "log", null_value = 1)
      )
    )
  })
}
For inputs that change frequently (sliders), debounce to avoid excessive re-renders:
filter_value &lt;- reactive(input$min_n) |&gt;
  shiny::debounce(300)

Split Tables in Shiny
Use splitTabvizOutput() / renderSplitTabviz() for a SplitForest. Programmatically focus a subgroup with split_tabviz_select():
ui &lt;- fluidPage(
  selectInput("region", "Region",
    choices = c("North America", "Europe", "Asia Pacific")),
  splitTabvizOutput("split_plot", height = "700px")
)

server &lt;- function(input, output, session) {
  output$split_plot &lt;- renderSplitTabviz({
    tabviz(trial_data,
      label = "study",
      columns = list(
        viz_forest(point = "hr", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
                   scale = "log", null_value = 1)
      )
    ) |&gt;
      split_table(by = "region")
  })

  observeEvent(input$region, {
    split_tabviz_select(split_tabviz_proxy("split_plot"), input$region)
  })
}

Customizing Group Headers
Control the visual styling of group headers at each level using theme modifiers:


Code
custom_theme &lt;- web_theme_cochrane() |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L1", "bg"),            "#E0F2FE") |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L1", "text", "size"),  "1.1rem") |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L1", "text", "weight"), 700) |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L2", "bg"),            "#F0F9FF") |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L2", "text", "italic"), TRUE) |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L2", "text", "size"),  "0.95rem") |&gt;
  set_spacing(indent_per_level = 20)

forest_plot(hierarchical_data,
  point = "or", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
  label = "study",
  group = c("region", "country"),
  null_value = 1, scale = "log",
  theme = custom_theme
)


The row_group cluster is one of the v2 theme’s Tier 3 component clusters. Its three tiers — L1 (outermost), L2, L3 — each carry bg, fg, rule, text (a TextRole bundle: family / size / weight / italic), and border_bottom. See Themes guide for the full structure and Themes Reference for the class definitions.

Web Integration

DownloadButton.svelte
The download button calls the same generator directly:
import { exportToSVG, exportToPNG } from "$lib/export";

async function handleExportSVG() {
  const svgString = exportToSVG(store.spec);
  // Create blob and trigger download
}


export.ts
Thin wrapper around svg-generator:
import { generateSVG, svgToBlob } from "./svg-generator";

export function exportToSVG(spec: WebSpec): string {
  return generateSVG(spec);
}

export async function exportToPNG(spec: WebSpec, scale = 2): Promise&lt;Blob&gt; {
  const svgString = generateSVG(spec);
  return svgToBlob(svgString, scale);  // Render to canvas, export
}

